body:
Right now, all outputs of a modules are forced to be a wire object, even if that output is a combinatorial signal instead of coming out of a FF.

For example, the assignment to `led` in [this code](https://github.com/tomverbeure/cxxrtl_eval/blob/6516b811e66b56022ef14bd6fbd00fedf8b18130/blink_basic/blink.v#L9), results in the following generated code:

```cpp
struct p_blink : public module {
	// \init: 0
	// \src: blink.v:4.16-4.23
	wire<12> p_counter {0u};
	// \src: blink.v:2.32-2.35
	/*output*/ wire<1> p_led;                            // <<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<< wire, not value!
	// \src: blink.v:2.20-2.23
	/*input*/ value<1> p_clk;
	value<1> prev_p_clk;
	bool posedge_p_clk() const {
		return !prev_p_clk.slice<0>().val() && p_clk.slice<0>().val();
	}

	bool eval() override;
	bool commit() override;
	void debug_info(debug_items &items, std::string path = "") override;
}; // struct p_blink
``` 

It also leads to the following Yosys warning, and wasted simulation cycles:
```
Module `blink' contains buffered combinatorial wires:
  led
Warning: Design contains buffered combinatorial wires, which require delta cycles during evaluation.
```

Since CXXRTL has get and set methods, it's not necessary anymore to force outputs to be wires for consistency, so it's better to make them values.

